: 0.9926299452781677, "span": {"begin": 470, "end": 474}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:117579"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "rx3", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9961386919021606, "span": {"begin": 515, "end": 518}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:8790"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "GFP", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9752445220947266, "span": {"begin": 519, "end": 522}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:65997"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "rasl11b mRNA", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9872063994407654, "span": {"begin": 576, "end": 588}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:65997"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "rasl11b", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9846144318580627, "span": {"begin": 608, "end": 615}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "RPC", "obj": "cell_type", "prob": 0.853155791759491, "span": {"begin": 638, "end": 641}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:65997"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "rasl11b", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9835341572761536, "span": {"begin": 713, "end": 720}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:65997"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "rasl11b", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9855027198791504, "span": {"begin": 780, "end": 787}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:57556"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "Sema6a", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.996537446975708, "span": {"begin": 832, "end": 838}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:5362"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "Plxna2", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9831540584564209, "span": {"begin": 839, "end": 845}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "RPC", "obj": "cell_type", "prob": 0.814163327217102, "span": {"begin": 890, "end": 893}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:57556"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "Sema6a", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9968067407608032, "span": {"begin": 995, "end": 1001}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:5362"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "Plxna2", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9804480671882629, "span": {"begin": 1002, "end": 1008}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "RPCs", "obj": "cell_type", "prob": 0.8014761209487915, "span": {"begin": 1069, "end": 1073}}, {"id": ["NCBITaxon:7955"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "zebrafish", "obj": "species", "prob": 0.8985727429389954, "span": {"begin": 1106, "end": 1115}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:65997"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "rasl11b", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.993645191192627, "span": {"begin": 1155, "end": 1162}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "RPCs", "obj": "cell_type", "prob": 0.7823939919471741, "span": {"begin": 1220, "end": 1224}}], "text": "It is hypothesized that Rasl11b acts as a negative regulator of MAPK by outcompeting Ras for its effectors such as Raf. After the overexpression of rasl11b, G0/G1 phase cell cycle arrest is induced and the proliferation of RPCs is inhibited (Emerson et al., 2017; He et al., 2018).      To determine if increased rasl11b expression contributes to decreased proliferation of RPCs, single-cell zebrafish embryos were injected with full-length rasl11b mRNA. Proliferation (pHH3) was visualized in the early eye field (rx3:GFP) of 18 somite embryos injected with 200 pg or 400 pg rasl11b mRNA. Overexpression of rasl11b resulted in decreased RPC proliferation in a dose-dependent manner. At 48 hpf, overexpression of rasl11b resulted in smaller eyes. (Emerson et al., 2017) show that rasl11b is negatively&nbsp; regulated downstream of Sema6a/Plxna2 signaling and when overexpressed, decreases RPC proliferation and eye size.      (Emerson et al., 2017) confirmed through morpholino knockdown, that Sema6a/Plxna2 signaling regulates proliferation and cohesive migration of RPCs in developing optic vesicles in zebrafish. Initial characterization of one gene, rasl11b, uncovered its contributing role to the proliferation of RPCs, providing insight into the mechanisms that control this key developmental process.", "timestamp": "Mon Jun 08 15:35:51 +0000 2026"}